39Weeks&1day, BABY WATCH is officially on!
Will this be my last photo update!?!? 

Feeling so over the indigestion, not being able to sleep & to top it all off… whatever the kids had that made them all mucousy & led to ear infections…. Joe & I now have. 

I feel SO sick right now… negative for all the testable illnesses. It’s just a horrible cold, but not being able to take medication & all these wonderful end of pregnancy symptoms… I just feel like a waste of life.

BUT in a way I'm glad that everyone was sick “Before” baby girl gets here. I just can’t imagine going into labor feeling this way & so sinusy.

 As much as I want her to come early…as of this morning I am now praying that I “get better” first. 

Having lots of anxiety about how this RSV season has been so bad. 
Cole being in preschool…
How are you guys dealing with having a toddler(s) & a baby in this season of sicknesses!?!

I can’t wait to meet this little angel baby ❤️

-Feeling so LOW, I tried to wear under the belly jeans the other day & had to yell for Joe to help get them off of me. It was SOOO uncomfortable! 

-No “cramp” like pains but tons of random Groin pain especially when she moves it's like sharp twinges (Is that the “lightning crotch”? Or is that pain more cervical… idk) but either way sometimes I feel like she is about to jump out.

-Braxton Hicks are strong & annoying🤨… 

-She is occasionally moving like crazy still! … it kinda hurts when she stretches out so much.

-haven’t experienced any “Mucous plug” or “bloody show” 😕… they said that they could do a cervical check at my appointment on the 8th & possibly do a membrane sweep if I wanted… so well see how I feel by then (I am not able to be “induced” in any way since it’s a 2nd TOLAC/VBAC)

I am not sleeping well at all… I dread going to bed. Even my elevated pillow fort is not helping.

 How are my other Mamas feeling who are due around now?! 
& or any advice for 2nd Vaginal delivery/ 2nd TOLAC|VBAC?! Hoping that its “quicker” like they say 🤪

I get it ….“when the baby is ready, she will come” … I agree 

I also am very anxious…🥹🤪🫠

I see things… I know things… my head starts to spiral…

They wanted to get me in for an NST/AFI for post dates (sorry for those of you who didn’t know the abbreviation on stories today🙈) (no I’m not in labor yet lol) 

NST- “A nonstress test is used to evaluate a baby’s health before birth. The goal of a nonstress test is to provide useful information about your baby’s oxygen supply by checking his or her heart rate and how it responds to your baby’s movement.”

AFI- “Amniotic fluid index is a quantitative estimate of amniotic fluid and an indicator of fetal well-being.”

Both of these were 👍 good & to be honest took away a TON of my anxiety… it was very reassuring to know all is well!

Our Birth story!❤️
12/18/22
2:30p- Braxton hicks started, very irregular, not painful or “crampy” at all, just a tightening at the top of my uterus

7pm- Sat on my ball &very shortly after dinner & started to get that lower more “Crampy” feeling.  They were quickly under 5-6minutes (But very irregular with some under 3 min apart according to my app!) 

8pm- my Mom was at our house to stay with the Kids & we were on our way to the hospital!!!

~8:30pm- L&D triage, contractions were SO intense! I was definitely dehydrated again🙈=Worsened the pain
 
They just kept saying I was in “Fierce Labor” 💀, First Check I was 6cm/ 70%, I was begging for an epidural
 
10:10pm- Epidural in. 9cm/100% & Basically said “I can Rupture you & we can do this right now”, I asked If we could just wait a little to give my body a break! She said ok, but it’s “GO TIME!!” When she gets back lol

The PRESSURE was CRAZY!!! (Since I got the Epidural “later” I was still feeling the pressure bad, but able to breathe through it SOO much better) 
It was like I had a bowling ball waiting to come out of my butt. 

11:37pm -When she went to check me again/tell me to start pushing my water popped & shot across the room like a super soaker (Some were “Hit”, I felt so bad!) 
Of course I asked what color it was… It was Meconium stained.
Right then I started to get in my head & Immediately was Nervous & Scared.

I knew NICU would now be at the delivery & that God forbid she was in any distress she would be in good hands! But def didn’t change how worried I felt.

Within 34min Baby Girl was out! 2nd degree tear, Cord was around her leg, but she was crying within a normal amount of time & Cleared by NICU. I was so relieved after. 

That was the MOST intense workout of my life! Day 2 the soreness from labor started to kick in!! Joe was ABSOLUTELY AMAZING!! Him & My Labor Nurse are ROCKSTARS!! (And must be so sore too!) My Midwife was an ANGEL!!! I don’t know how I would have done it ALL without her amazing support physically & emotionally!! Very blessed❤️

•Regulates body temperature

•Stabilizes the baby’s breathing, heartbeat, blood sugars & more (may also have a positive effect on the baby’s brain development)

•Encourages breastfeeding(your body also releases a hormone called prolactin, which stimulates milk production) 

•May reduce crying/improve sleep

•Helps your baby feel safe (recognize familiar sounds, like the sounds of your heartbeat and voice)

For Parents:

•helps BOTH Moms & Dads bond with their Newborn

•Promotes bonding (decreases in stress hormones)

•Reduces risk of postpartum depression, stress & anxiety
 
•Encourages breast milk production

•Helps increase confidence

When we decide to do a detox it was very random & spur of the moment. It was like a trigger was pulled & we just went Cold turkey. 

I was super pregnant with 2 kids … just giving in a lot. Then the baby came, I was tired, we were tired. The iPads started to become our baby sitter. 

They were waking up on them, winding down for sleep on them, tv on during meals & throughout the day… we didn’t have any boundaries left.

It was just a “season” … where we welcomed our 3rd baby & were “adjusting”. 

Not judging anyone at all by how much time their kids are on iPads/watching tv ! (We were doing it more than ever) and I know this is a very controversial topic.

I just wanted to share because so many have been asking “how is it going”… it has changed my kids for the BEST, better than I could have imagined! (I really didn’t truly think that taking screens away would impact them so much) 

We watched them begin to feel comfortable in the slow pace of everyday life.
It has lessened power struggles, decreased overstimulation, increased focus, improved bedtime/sleep, decreased fighting and screaming between the kids… theres just so much I can’t even begin to explain it all.

I read @jerricasannes free guide to detoxing & watched a lot of good videos she has linked that really convinced me (Ted talks etc) 

We will reintroduce it … but to be honest everytime we think about it .. there are just other things that end up happening that replace “that time” with family time/bonding/independent play… and we just have been easily gravitating towards those things more. 

This was harder for us than it was for the kids… ( if your kids are older I can see that being reversed & really tough) … but just wanted to say it was worth it 

6wks (going on 7wks) screen free at home.

(This swing has been a great addition to help them get bursts of energy out especially when it’s too cold or rainy & we don’t get outside) linked it on my LTK in bio 🙃

Ever since mentioning that my Newborn was “Sleeping the night” I’ve had so many questions asking “How, What, When, where” 
I can’t promise but I can tell you what we do & how it has been working beautifully for us
To start, we only put her in her @lovetoDream Transition Bag at night! (I strongly feel that saving this special comfort for night is a great way to signal “bedtime”)

For us Bedtime goes like this:
-Bath (Not everyday)
-salt lamp [on]
-white noise [on]
-baby to changing table (We call this her “Smile table”)
-day time outfit off
-baby kisses, belly rubs, bicycles (This is the time we use to help “Wind” baby) if showing signs of being gassy
-diaper change (& a skin protectant on)
-jammies
-@Lovetodream Transition Bag
-Breastfeeding, rocking, hiney pats & More kisses
-burping 
-Paci
-into the Bedside bassinet 

What is your night routine like?! Do you swaddle?

I have swaddled all 3 of my babies, then transitioned them out. The Love to dream swaddles are so amazing and easy to transition with the zip off wings! Both arms in always allowed us to really get the rest we needed in the newborn/infant stage, then slowly transitioning to both arms out when they started showing signs of trying to roll

*disclaimer- remember every baby is different & not all babies sleep “through the night” from 6 weeks!

If you are or know someone who is pumping Save, Like & Share this helpful info❤️

Pumping doesn’t have to be a pain! Learn about the importance of flange sizing for comfortable & efficient breast pumping. 🤱🏼💕

I’m a Mother Baby Nurse Currently pumping for my 4 month old when working. 
I work with some AMAZING IBCLC (Lactation consultants) & am very passionate about helping Mamas navigate the craziness that comes with breastfeeding & Pumping. 

I can tell you I saw a SIGNIFICANT difference in my Milk output when using the correct size flange(Flange insert) & it’s COMFORTABLE!

I Just can’t believe that I found out about these inserts at the END of my pumping/breastfeeding journey with my 2nd baby. 

To find your correct flange size, measure your nipple diameter, you can then get that size flange insert or some advise to add 2mm for comfortable suction. A proper fit will help prevent discomfort, pain & low milk output.

Also your sizing may differ from left and right so measure both! 

If you are still in pain or uncomfortable pumping or breastfeeding please contact an IBCLC (Lactation consultant) in your area! You can contact your hospital or google “IBCLC near me”

It’s important to remember that every baby is different & may take longer to adjust to these transitions!

Here are some things we found to be helpful:

1. Start practicing Naps in the crib
2. Familiarize baby with their new room by: doing diaper changes in there, getting dressed & playing 
3. Start doing “bedtime routine” in the nursery (while still sleeping in their usual room) to start to show that this is a “safe place”
4. To slowly transition to the new room you can bring their bassinet into the nursery
5. Then finally move baby into the crib… & cross your fingers🤪☺️❤️

Did you have Postpartum BO?  WHY does this happen!?

…Hormonal changes are dramatic in the postpartum period (Especially while breastfeeding) These hormones can affect your body odor.🤢

For me it was so embarrassing. I didn’t want to leave the house (Seems so silly but this odor really added to the crazy ups & downs of “4th trimester”) it didn’t matter what soap or deodorant I used (I do really try to stick with the natural, “Better for you” brands with all of that.) 

But anyway for me something as simple as lime made such a difference. 
I’m sure people are going to find something to say about this 😎but…I was at my wits end & this helped me. 🥰

Lime contains citric acid, which has antibacterial properties that can help neutralize odor-causing bacteria. When applied to the skin, the acidic nature of this fruit can reduce the unpleasant smell associated with body odor. Basically inhibits the growth of odor-causing bacteria…
(& like always the effectiveness may vary from person to person)

So I’m curious… have you tried this? Did it help
This would be great for young men going through those hormonal stinky changes also.

Few things:
•Citric acid can be irritating, don’t do this just after shaving 💀

•Let the lime dry before putting on clothes

•Just a few times a week can really help keep BO under control, while also using your regular deodorant (don’t use lime too frequent to avoid affecting pH balance☺)

•Avoid sun exposure or tanning when you do this regimen.

Incorporating proper body mechanics into your daily routine may take a bit of practice, but the benefits are undeniable.

When it comes to picking up your baby or kids, using your arms instead of relying solely on your hips can significantly improve your body alignment. Holding your child close to your chest while engaging your arms and core ensures that your spine remains aligned, reducing strain on your back and promoting better posture.

By actively using your arms to lift and carry, you’re providing your muscles with a gentle workout. Over time, this can lead to improved arm strength and definition💪🏻

Teaching yourself proper body mechanics from the start is key to preventing injury! 

Incorporating mindful practices into your routine not only enhances your own physical health but also deepens the emotional bonds with your little ones. So, as you lift your baby or kids into your arms, remember that you’re not just cradling their preciousness, but also embracing a journey of growth, strength, and connection for both of you🥰🤩
